I will have poached eggs.

470
00:36:40,323 --> 00:36:42,659
And bring me some cigars, please.
Havana cigars.

471
00:36:42,826 --> 00:36:46,162
And that will be all for you, sir?
I'll see to it right away.

472
00:36:46,287 --> 00:36:49,457
Try one of these Jamaican cigars,
ambassador. They're good.

473
00:36:49,582 --> 00:36:52,961
Thank you, no. I do not support
the work of imperialist stooges.

474
00:36:53,086 --> 00:36:55,630
Oh, only Commie stooges, huh?

475
00:36:56,256 --> 00:36:58,007
Mr President.

476
00:36:59,134 --> 00:37:02,804
You're gonna let that lousy Commie
punk vomit all over us like this?

477
00:37:02,929 --> 00:37:03,847
Mr President?

478
00:37:04,347 --> 00:37:07,642
They haven't reached Premier Kissoff.
They don't know where he is...

479
00:37:07,767 --> 00:37:10,812
...and he won't be back
for another two hours.

480
00:37:10,979 --> 00:37:13,356
-Try B86543 Moscow.
-Yes, sir.

481
00:37:13,481 --> 00:37:15,817
You'd never have found him
through his office.

482
00:37:15,942 --> 00:37:19,779
Our premier is a man of the people,
but he is also a man, if you follow.

483
00:37:19,904 --> 00:37:22,532
-Degenerate, atheistic Commie.
-What did you say?

484
00:37:22,657 --> 00:37:26,161
I said, Premier Kissoff is
a degenerate, atheistic Commie!

485
00:37:26,286 --> 00:37:29,164
-Have this ignorant fool--
-I'm sorry!

486
00:37:29,289 --> 00:37:33,209
Mr President,
I think they're trying the number.

487
00:37:43,845 --> 00:37:46,973
Gentlemen, you can't fight in here.
This is the war room!

488
00:37:47,098 --> 00:37:49,851
What is going on here?
I demand an explanation.

489
00:37:49,976 --> 00:37:53,938
This clumsy fool tried to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

490
00:37:53,980 --> 00:37:56,858
You bet your sweets, Mr Commie!
Look at this.

491
00:37:56,983 --> 00:38:01,446
This lousy Commie rat was taking
pictures with this, of the big board!

492
00:38:01,654 --> 00:38:03,490
Mr Ambassador!

493
00:38:03,823 --> 00:38:08,036
This clumsy fool attempted to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

494
00:38:08,161 --> 00:38:10,914
That's a damn lie!
I saw him with my own eyes.

495
00:38:11,039 --> 00:38:15,210
This is outrageous. I have never heard
of such behaviour in the war room.

496
00:38:15,335 --> 00:38:18,713
Mr President, I think
they're getting him on the line.

497
00:38:45,824 --> 00:38:47,742
You gotta hand it to
those Commies.

498
00:38:47,867 --> 00:38:49,410
Yeah.

499
00:38:49,536 --> 00:38:52,288
Those trucks sure look like
the real thing, don't they?

500
00:38:52,455 --> 00:38:54,290
I wonder
where they got them from.

501
00:38:54,457 --> 00:38:57,752
Probably bought them
from the Army as war surplus.

502
00:39:00,380 --> 00:39:04,509
Okay, open up at 200 yards.

503
00:40:01,649 --> 00:40:05,361
Tell him where you are and that
you'll speak if I say anything untrue...

504
00:40:05,486 --> 00:40:08,698
...but please don't tell him
anything more than that.

505
00:40:09,324 --> 00:40:13,536
Alexi? Alexi, please. I beg you.

506
00:40:13,786 --> 00:40:16,372
But I don't have a phone.

507
00:40:16,497 --> 00:40:18,583
Give him your phone, Frank.

508
00:40:45,818 --> 00:40:50,239
I've done as you asked.
Be careful. I think he is drunk.

509
00:40:53,201 --> 00:40:57,664
Hello? Hello, Dimitri?

510
00:40:57,789 --> 00:40:59,540
Listen, I can't hear too well.

511
00:40:59,666 --> 00:41:03,419
Do you suppose you could
turn the music down just a little?

512
00:41:03,586 --> 00:41:05,421
Oh, that's much better.

513
00:41:05,672 --> 00:41:08,341
Yeah. Yes.

514
00:41:09,550 --> 00:41:12,345
Fine. I can hear you now, Dimitri.

515
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:15,890
Clear and plain
and coming through fine.

516
00:41:16,015 --> 00:41:20,395
I'm coming through fine too?
Good. Then....

517
00:41:20,520 --> 00:41:24,399
Well, then, as you say,
we're both coming through fine. Good.

518
00:41:24,524 --> 00:41:28,736
Well, it's good that you're fine
and I'm fine.

519
00:41:28,861 --> 00:41:32,115
I agree with you.
It's great to be fine.

520
00:41:32,991 --> 00:41:35,118
Now then, Dimitri...

521
00:41:35,243 --> 00:41:40,915
...you know how we've always talked
about the possibility...

522
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:43,751
...of something going wrong
with the bomb.

523
00:41:45,086 --> 00:41:47,088
The bomb, Dimitri.

524
00:41:48,089 --> 00:41:50,883
The hydrogen bomb.

525
00:41:51,009 --> 00:41:53,928
Well, now, what happened is...

526
00:41:54,053 --> 00:41:58,224
...one of our base commanders,
he had a sort of--

527
00:41:58,349 --> 00:42:01,477
Well, he went a little funny
in the head.

528
00:42:01,644 --> 00:42:04,647
You know, just a little funny.

529
00:42:04,772 --> 00:42:09,318
And he went and did a silly thing.

530
00:42:09,444 --> 00:42:13,823
Well, I'll tell you what he did.
He ordered his planes...

531
00:42:15,283 --> 00:42:17,952
...to attack your country.

532
00:42:18,077 --> 00:42:20,455
Well, let me finish, Dimitri.

533
00:42:21,414 --> 00:42:23,332
Let me finish, Dimitri.

534
00:42:23,458 --> 00:42:26,627
Well, listen, how do you think
I feel about it?

535
00:42:26,753 --> 00:42:29,630
Can you imagine how I feel
about it, Dimitri?

536
00:42:31,132 --> 00:42:35,470
Why do you think I'm calling you?
Just to say hello?

537
00:42:36,471 --> 00:42:38,848
Of course I like to speak to you!

538
00:42:38,973 --> 00:42:41,476
Of course I like to say hello!

539
00:42:41,601 --> 00:42:43,686
Not now, but any time, Dimitri.

540
00:42:43,811 --> 00:42:47,815
I'm just calling up to tell you
something terrible has happened.

541
00:42:47,940 --> 00:42:50,860
Of course it's a friendly call.

542
00:42:50,985 --> 00:42:55,323
Listen, if it wasn't friendly, you
probably wouldn't have even got it.

543
00:42:57,575 --> 00:43:02,330
They will not reach their targets
for at least another hour.

544
00:43:02,455 --> 00:43:05,500
I am-- I am positive, Dimitri.

545
00:43:05,625 --> 00:43:08,002
I've been all over this
with your ambassador.

546
00:43:08,127 --> 00:43:10,546
It is not a trick.

547
00:43:10,671 --> 00:43:12,048
Well, I'll tell you.

548
00:43:12,215 --> 00:43:16,010
We'd like to give your air staff
a complete rundown on the targets...

549
00:43:16,135 --> 00:43:19,347
...the flight plans and the
defensive systems of the planes.

550
00:43:19,472 --> 00:43:24,352
Yes, I mean, if we're unable
to recall the planes...

551
00:43:24,477 --> 00:43:27,146
...then I'd say that, well...

552
00:43:28,481 --> 00:43:32,860
...we're just gonna have to help you
destroy them, Dimitri.

553
00:43:32,985 --> 00:43:35,863
I know they're our boys.

554
00:43:35,988 --> 00:43:38,533
All right, listen.
Now, who should we call?

555
00:43:40,326 --> 00:43:45,498
Who should we call, Dimitri?
Sorry, you faded away there.

556
00:43:45,832 --> 00:43:49,877
The People's Central
Air Defence Headquarters.

557
00:43:50,002 --> 00:43:52,213
Where is that, Dimitri?

558
00:43:52,338 --> 00:43:54,507
In Omsk. Right.

559
00:43:55,508 --> 00:43:56,759
Yes.

560
00:43:56,884 --> 00:43:59,804
Oh, you'll call them first, will you?

561
00:44:01,055 --> 00:44:04,225
Do you happen to have
the phone number on you, Dimitri?

562
00:44:05,893 --> 00:44:09,105
What? I see.
Just ask for Omsk information.

563
00:44:10,857 --> 00:44:15,236
I'm sorry too, Dimitri.
I'm very sorry.

564
00:44:15,361 --> 00:44:19,240
All right, you're sorrier than I am.
But I am sorry as well.

565
00:44:21,492 --> 00:44:23,744
I am as sorry as you are, Dimitri.

566
00:44:23,870 --> 00:44:25,746
Don't say that you're more sorry...

567
00:44:25,872 --> 00:44:28,791
...because I'm capable of being
just as sorry as you are.

568
00:44:28,916 --> 00:44:32,336
So we're both sorry, all right?
All right.

569
00:44:33,546 --> 00:44:37,842
Yes, he's right here. Yes, he wants
to talk to you. Just a second.

570
00:44:50,897 --> 00:44:52,607
What?

571
00:45:10,416 --> 00:45:13,586
What? What is it? What?

572
00:45:13,711 --> 00:45:16,756
The fools. The mad fools.

573
00:45:17,924 --> 00:45:19,926
What's happened?

574
00:45:20,051 --> 00:45:22,637
The doomsday machine.

575
00:45:22,762 --> 00:45:25,306
The doom--? The doomsday machine?
What is that?

576
00:45:25,431 --> 00:45:30,770
A device which will destroy
all human and animal life on Earth.

577
00:45:30,895 --> 00:45:33,147
All human and animal life?

578
00:45:47,662 --> 00:45:50,331
-Mandrake?
-Yes, Jack?

579
00:45:51,374 --> 00:45:54,961
Have you ever seen a Commie
drink a glass of water?

580
00:45:55,086 --> 00:45:59,674
Well, no, I can't say I have, Jack.

581
00:46:00,800 --> 00:46:05,680
Vodka. That's what they drink,
isn't it? Never water.

582
00:46:05,805 --> 00:46:10,142
Well, I believe that's
what they drink, Jack, yes.

583
00:46:10,268 --> 00:46:13,688
On no account will a Commie
ever drink water...

584
00:46:13,813 --> 00:46:16,148
...and not without good reason.

585
00:46:17,149 --> 00:46:19,819
Oh, yes.

586
00:46:19,944 --> 00:46:25,992
I can't quite see
what you're getting at, Jack.

587
00:46:26,117 --> 00:46:29,870
Water.
That's what I'm getting at, water.

588
00:46:30,830 --> 00:46:34,375
Mandrake, water is the source
of all life.

589
00:46:35,835 --> 00:46:39,422
Seven-tenths of this Earth's surface
is water.

590
00:46:39,547 --> 00:46:41,966
Why, do you realise that...

591
00:46:42,967 --> 00:46:45,928
...70 percent of you is water?

592
00:46:46,053 --> 00:46:47,430
Good Lord.

593
00:46:47,555 --> 00:46:52,685
And as human beings,
you and I need fresh, pure water...

594
00:46:52,810 --> 00:46:56,355
...to replenish
our precious bodily fluids.

595
00:46:56,480 --> 00:46:59,233
-You beginning to understand?
-Yes.

596
00:47:02,653 --> 00:47:04,572
Mandrake....

597
00:47:06,532 --> 00:47:11,746
Mandrake, have you never wondered
why I drink only distilled water...

598
00:47:11,871 --> 00:47:16,250
...0r rainwater,
and only pure grain alcohol?

599
00:47:16,375 --> 00:47:19,628
Well, it did occur to me, Jack, yes.

600
00:47:20,713 --> 00:47:25,468
Have you ever heard of a thing called
fluoridation? Fluoridation of water?

601
00:47:25,760 --> 00:47:29,597
Yes, I have heard of that, Jack, yes.
Yes.

602
00:47:29,722 --> 00:47:31,599
Well, do you know what it is?

603
00:47:31,724 --> 00:47:34,769
No. No, I don't know what it is, no.

604
00:47:34,894 --> 00:47:38,773
Do you realise that fluoridation...

605
00:47:38,898 --> 00:47:41,650
...Is the most
monstrously conceived...

606
00:47:41,776 --> 00:47:45,279
...and dangerous Communist plot
we have ever had to face?

607
00:47:51,243 --> 00:47:53,162
Two can play at that game, soldier.

608
00:47:58,084 --> 00:48:00,836
That's nice shooting, soldier!

609
00:48:25,277 --> 00:48:27,321
Mandrake, come here.

610
00:48:27,613 --> 00:48:29,365
You calling me, Jack?

611
00:48:29,532 --> 00:48:31,992
Come over here
and help me with this belt.

612
00:48:34,954 --> 00:48:37,957
I haven't had
very much experience...

613
00:48:38,082 --> 00:48:40,835
...you know,
with those sort of machines, Jack...

614
00:48:40,960 --> 00:48:44,505
...I've only ever pressed a button
in my old Spitfire.

615
00:48:44,630 --> 00:48:48,551
In the name of Her Majesty and the
Continental Congress, feed the belt.

616
00:48:48,676 --> 00:48:53,222
Jack, I'd love to come,
but what's happened, you see...

617
00:48:53,347 --> 00:48:56,183
...the string in my leg's gone.

618
00:48:57,184 --> 00:48:59,812
-The what?
-The string. I never told you...

619
00:48:59,937 --> 00:49:05,151
...but, you see, I've got a gammy leg.
Oh, dear. Gone. Shot off.

620
00:49:07,111 --> 00:49:10,823
Mandrake, come over here.
The redcoats are coming. Come on!

621
00:49:11,866 --> 00:49:16,036
When it is detonated, it will produce
enough radioactive fallout...

622
00:49:16,162 --> 00:49:18,038
...So that in 10 months...

623
00:49:18,164 --> 00:49:21,208
...the surface of the Earth
will be as dead as the moon.

624
00:49:21,333 --> 00:49:24,086
Come on, de Sadesky!
That's ridiculous!

625
00:49:24,211 --> 00:49:26,255
Our studies show
even the worst fallout...

626
00:49:26,380 --> 00:49:28,507
...iIs down to a safe level
after two weeks.

627
00:49:28,632 --> 00:49:32,344
You've obviously never heard
of cobalt thorium G.

628
00:49:32,469 --> 00:49:33,762
No, what about it?

629
00:49:33,888 --> 00:49:37,725
Cobalt thorium G has
a radioactive half-life of 93 years.

630
00:49:37,850 --> 00:49:40,895
If you take, say, 50 H bombs
in the 100 megatonne range...

631
00:49:41,020 --> 00:49:43,355
...and jacket them
with cobalt thorium G...

632
00:49:43,480 --> 00:49:48,068
...when they are exploded, they will
produce a doomsday shroud...

633
00:49:48,194 --> 00:49:50,404
...a lethal cloud of radioactivity...

634
00:49:50,529 --> 00:49:54,909
...which will encircle the Earth
for 93 years!

635
00:49:55,034 --> 00:49:58,621
What a load of Commie bull.
I mean, after all....

636
00:49:59,663 --> 00:50:02,082
I'm afraid I don't understand
something, Alexi.

637
00:50:02,541 --> 00:50:06,086
Is the premier threatening to
explode it if we carry out the attack?

638
00:50:06,212 --> 00:50:08,464
No. It is not a thing
a sane man would do.

639
00:50:08,631 --> 00:50:11,926
The doomsday machine is designed
to trigger itself automatically.

640
00:50:12,051 --> 00:50:13,969
But surely you can
disarm it somehow.

641
00:50:14,094 --> 00:50:17,973
No. It is designed to explode if
any attempt is made to un-trigger it.

642
00:50:18,098 --> 00:50:19,308
Automatically?

643
00:50:19,433 --> 00:50:21,977
It's a Commie trick!
We're wasting valuable time!

644
00:50:22,102 --> 00:50:25,314
Look at the big board!
They're getting ready to clobber us!

645
00:50:25,439 --> 00:50:29,902
But this is absolute madness.
Why should you build such a thing?

646
00:50:30,027 --> 00:50:31,654
Some of us fought against it.

647
00:50:31,779 --> 00:50:35,407
But we could not keep up with the
expense involved in the arms race...

648
00:50:35,533 --> 00:50:38,661
...the space race
and the peace race.

649
00:50:39,078 --> 00:50:41,288
At the same time,
our people grumbled...

650
00:50:41,413 --> 00:50:43,958
...for more nylons
and washing machines.

651
00:50:44,083 --> 00:50:46,627
Our doomsday scheme cost us
a small fraction...

652
00:50:46,752 --> 00:50:49,838
...of what we had been spending
on defence in a single year.

653
00:50:49,964 --> 00:50:52,800
The deciding factor was
when we learned your country...

654
00:50:52,925 --> 00:50:56,428
...was working along similar lines.
We were afraid of a doomsday gap.

655
00:50:56,554 --> 00:50:59,848
This is preposterous! I've never
approved of anything like that.

656
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:02,768
Our source was
The New York Times.

657
00:51:03,644 --> 00:51:07,022
Dr. Strangelove, do we have anything
like that in the works?

658
00:51:07,189 --> 00:51:10,025
A moment, please, Mr President.

659
00:51:12,403 --> 00:51:15,823
Under the authority granted me...

660
00:51:15,948 --> 00:51:19,868
...as director of weapons research
and development...

661
00:51:19,994 --> 00:51:24,331
...I commissioned last year
a study of this project...

662
00:51:24,456 --> 00:51:26,625
...by the Bland Corporation.

663
00:51:26,750 --> 00:51:29,545
Based on the findings
of the report...

664
00:51:29,670 --> 00:51:35,217
...my conclusion was that this idea
was not a practical deterrent...

665
00:51:35,342 --> 00:51:39,346
...for reasons which at this moment
must be all too obvious.

666
00:51:39,471 --> 00:51:42,850
Then you mean it is possible
for them to have built such a thing?

667
00:51:46,812 --> 00:51:51,859
Mr President, the technology required
is easily within the means...

668
00:51:51,984 --> 00:51:56,322
...of even the smallest
nuclear power.

669
00:51:56,447 --> 00:52:01,201
It requires only the will to do so.

670
00:52:01,368 --> 00:52:04,913
But how is it possible for this thing
to be triggered automatically...

671
00:52:05,039 --> 00:52:07,541
...and at the same time
impossible to un-trigger?

672
00:52:07,666 --> 00:52:11,712
Mr President,
it is not only possible...

673
00:52:11,837 --> 00:52:13,714
...it is essential.

674
00:52:13,839 --> 00:52:18,218
That is the whole idea
of this machine, you know.

675
00:52:18,344 --> 00:52:23,515
Deterrence is the art of producing
in the mind of the enemy...

676
00:52:23,641 --> 00:52:26,185
...the fear to attack.

677
00:52:26,310 --> 00:52:31,190
And so because of the automated and
irrevocable decision-making process...

678
00:52:31,315 --> 00:52:35,110
...which rules out
human meddling...

679
00:52:35,277 --> 00:52:39,198
...the doomsday machine
is terrifying.

680
00:52:39,323 --> 00:52:41,367
This is simple to understand.

681
00:52:41,492 --> 00:52:44,620
And completely credible
and convincing.

682
00:52:44,745 --> 00:52:47,790
Gee, I wish we had one of them
doomsday machines, Stainesy.

683
00:52:47,915 --> 00:52:52,211
But this is fantastic, Strangelove.
How can it be triggered automatically?

684
00:52:52,336 --> 00:52:56,090
Well, it's remarkably simple
to do that.

685
00:52:56,215 --> 00:52:59,635
When you merely wish
to bury bombs...

686
00:52:59,802 --> 00:53:02,096
...there's no limit to the size.

687
00:53:02,221 --> 00:53:08,310
After that, they are connected
to a gigantic complex of computers.

688
00:53:08,435 --> 00:53:14,274
Now, then: a specific and
clearly-defined set of circumstances...

689
00:53:14,400 --> 00:53:17,820
...under which the bombs
are to be exploded...

690
00:53:17,945 --> 00:53:21,949
...Is programmed into
a tape memory bank.

691
00:53:22,074 --> 00:53:25,911
-A single roll of tape can store....
-Strangelove.

692
00:53:26,036 --> 00:53:29,248
What kind of a name is that?
That ain't no Kraut name, is it?

693
00:53:29,373 --> 00:53:31,625
He changed it
when he became a citizen.

694
00:53:31,750 --> 00:53:34,336
It used to be Merkwdurdigliebe.

695
00:53:34,461 --> 00:53:39,174
Well, a Kraut by any other name,
huh, Stainesy?

696
00:53:41,051 --> 00:53:45,347
--is that the whole point of
the doomsday machine...

697
00:53:45,472 --> 00:53:49,017
...Is lost if you keep it a secret.

698
00:53:49,143 --> 00:53:51,270
Why didn't you tell the world?

699
00:53:51,395 --> 00:53:55,691
It was to be announced
at the Party Congress on Monday.

700
00:53:55,858 --> 00:53:59,153
As you know,
the premier loves surprises.

701
00:54:47,659 --> 00:54:49,912
Stay with me, Mandrake.

702
00:54:54,875 --> 00:54:57,753
All right, Mandrake, now feed me.
Feed me bullets.

703
00:55:27,574 --> 00:55:32,621
Jack, don't you think we'd be better off
away from all this flying glass?

704
00:55:32,746 --> 00:55:34,873
No, we're okay here.

705
00:55:36,083 --> 00:55:40,128
Mandrake, do you realise that in
addition to fluoridating water, why...

706
00:55:40,254 --> 00:55:43,757
...there are studies underway
to fluoridate salt, flour...

707
00:55:43,882 --> 00:55:48,887
...fruit juices, soup, sugar,
milk, ice cream?

708
00:55:49,012 --> 00:55:50,472
Ice cream, Mandrake.

709
00:55:50,597 --> 00:55:52,975
-Children's ice cream.
-Good Lord.

710
00:55:53,100 --> 00:55:55,269
You know when fluoridation
first began?

711
00:55:56,603 --> 00:55:58,313
No, I don't, Jack.

712
00:55:58,438 --> 00:56:00,774
1946.

713
00:56:00,899 --> 00:56:03,610
1946, Mandrake.

714
00:56:04,027 --> 00:56:07,948
How does that coincide with your
postwar Commie conspiracy, huh?

715
00:56:08,073 --> 00:56:11,326
It's incredibly obvious, isn't it?

716
00:56:11,451 --> 00:56:16,957
A foreign substance is introduced
into our precious bodily fluids...

717
00:56:17,082 --> 00:56:20,294
...without the knowledge
of the individual.

718
00:56:20,419 --> 00:56:23,088
Certainly without any choice.

719
00:56:24,089 --> 00:56:27,467
That's the way
a hard-core Commie works.

720
00:56:28,802 --> 00:56:32,014
Jack. Listen, tell me--
Tell me, Jack.

721
00:56:32,139 --> 00:56:37,686
When did you first become--
Well, develop this theory?

722
00:56:38,770 --> 00:56:40,981
Well, I....

723
00:56:41,106 --> 00:56:44,610
I first became aware of it,
Mandrake...

724
00:56:44,735 --> 00:56:47,529
...during the physical act of love.

725
00:56:48,447 --> 00:56:52,701
Yes, a profound sense of fatigue...

726
00:56:52,826 --> 00:56:55,329
...a feeling of emptiness followed.

727
00:56:55,954 --> 00:57:00,000
Luckily, I was able to interpret
these feelings correctly.

728
00:57:00,626 --> 00:57:02,294
Loss of essence.

729
00:57:04,129 --> 00:57:07,549
I can assure you it has not recurred,
Mandrake.

730
00:57:07,674 --> 00:57:11,803
Women sense my power...

731
00:57:11,928 --> 00:57:14,640
...and they seek the life essence.

732
00:57:15,265 --> 00:57:18,560
-I do not avoid women, Mandrake.
-No.

733
00:57:18,685 --> 00:57:21,521
But I do deny them my essence.

734
00:57:21,939 --> 00:57:24,524
Yes, yes, Jack.

735
00:57:37,371 --> 00:57:39,331
Cease fire!

736
00:58:00,560 --> 00:58:02,229
My boys must have surrendered.

737
00:58:02,354 --> 00:58:04,606
Well, there it is.

738
00:58:04,731 --> 00:58:06,566
Now, Jack, listen.

739
00:58:06,692 --> 00:58:10,028
While there's still time, I beg you,
let's recall the wing and--

740
00:58:12,114 --> 00:58:15,409
Those boys were like my children,
Mandrake.

741
00:58:16,535 --> 00:58:20,080
-Now they let me down.
-No, no, Jack, not a bit of it.

742
00:58:20,122 --> 00:58:23,208
No, I'm sure they all gave it
their very best.

743
00:58:23,333 --> 00:58:25,794
I'm equally sure they all died
thinking of you...

744
00:58:25,919 --> 00:58:28,588
...every man jack of them, Jack.

745
00:58:29,089 --> 00:58:31,258
Supposing a bit of water
has gone off, eh?

746
00:58:31,383 --> 00:58:33,760
One can never be too sure
about those things.

747
00:58:33,885 --> 00:58:36,722
But you look at me.
Do I look all rancid and clotted?

748
00:58:36,847 --> 00:58:39,599
You look at me, Jack. Look.

749
00:58:39,725 --> 00:58:43,770
And I drink a lot of water, you know.
I'm what you might call a water man.

750
00:58:43,895 --> 00:58:47,149
And I can swear to you,
my boy, swear to you...

751
00:58:47,274 --> 00:58:52,112
...that there's nothing wrong with
my bodily fluids. Not a thing, Jackie.

752
00:58:52,237 --> 00:58:54,448
Mandrake, were you ever
a prisoner of war?

753
00:58:54,573 --> 00:58:58,160
Well, Jack,
the time's running very--

754
00:58:58,285 --> 00:59:01,329
-What?
-Were you ever a prisoner of war?

755
00:59:01,455 --> 00:59:03,498
Yes, I was,
as a matter of fact, Jack.

756
00:59:03,623 --> 00:59:06,668
Did they torture you?

757
00:59:06,793 --> 00:59:10,255
Yes, they did. I was tortured
by the Japanese, if you must know.

758
00:59:10,380 --> 00:59:13,175
-Not a pretty story.
-What happened?

759
00:59:13,300 --> 00:59:17,512
I don't know, Jack. It's difficult
to think of under these conditions.

760
00:59:17,679 --> 00:59:19,848
Well, what happened was...

761
00:59:20,182 --> 00:59:23,310
...they got me on the old
Rangoon-Inchinawa Railway.

762
00:59:23,435 --> 00:59:27,773
I was laying train lines
for the bloody Japanese puff-puffs.

763
00:59:27,898 --> 00:59:31,151
No, I mean, when they tortured you,
did you talk?

764
00:59:32,819 --> 00:59:34,821
No, I....

765
00:59:34,946 --> 00:59:39,159
Well, I don't think they wanted me
to talk, really, or say anything.

766
00:59:39,284 --> 00:59:42,329
It was their way of having
a bit of fun, the swines.

767
00:59:42,454 --> 00:59:45,999
The strange thing is they make
such bloody good cameras.

768
00:59:47,834 --> 00:59:50,003
Those clowns outside
are gonna give me...

769
00:59:50,128 --> 00:59:53,507
...a pretty good going-over
in a few minutes for the code.

770
00:59:53,799 --> 00:59:55,133
Yes--

771
00:59:56,301 --> 00:59:59,888
Yes, well, you may have....
May have quite a point there, Jack.

772
01:00:00,806 --> 01:00:03,725
I don't know how well
I could stand up under torture.

773
01:00:03,850 --> 01:00:07,062
Well, of course, the answer to that is,
boy, no one ever does.

774
01:00:07,229 --> 01:00:11,316
And my advice to you, Jack,
is to give me the code now.

775
01:00:11,441 --> 01:00:14,236
And if those devils come back
and try any rough stuff...

776
01:00:14,361 --> 01:00:17,864
...we'll fight them together,
like we did just now on the floor.

777
01:00:17,989 --> 01:00:21,201
You with your gun and me with a belt
and the ammo, feeding you.

778
01:00:21,326 --> 01:00:24,329
"Feed me," you said,
and I was feeding you, Jack.

779
01:00:24,454 --> 01:00:26,832
You know, Mandrake...

780
01:00:26,957 --> 01:00:30,210
...I happen to believe in a life
after this one...

781
01:00:31,670 --> 01:00:35,090
...and I know I'll have to answer
for what I've done.

782
01:00:36,883 --> 01:00:38,385
And I think I can.

783
01:00:38,510 --> 01:00:41,888
Yes, well, of course you can, Jack.
Of course you can. You can.

784
01:00:42,013 --> 01:00:44,224
I'm a religious man myself,
you know, Jack.

785
01:00:44,349 --> 01:00:48,103
I believe in all that sort of thing
and I'm hoping, you know, Jack....

786
01:00:48,228 --> 01:00:51,064
You've dropped your gun, Jack.
Yes.... You know what...?

787
01:00:51,189 --> 01:00:54,734
No, Jack, let me take that for you.
I'll take that for you, Jack.

788
01:00:54,860 --> 01:00:59,072
You know what I'm hoping? I'm hoping
you're going to give me the code.

789
01:00:59,197 --> 01:01:02,701
And-- You're going to have a wash
and brush up? What a good idea.

790
01:01:02,826 --> 01:01:05,370
Always did wonders for a man,
a wash and brush up.

791
01:01:05,495 --> 01:01:08,290
Water on the back of the neck
makes you feel marvellous.

792
01:01:08,415 --> 01:01:11,084
That's what we need,
water on the neck and the code.

793
01:01:11,209 --> 01:01:14,713
Now, supposing I play a little
guessing game with you, Jack, boy.

794
01:01:14,838 --> 01:01:17,591
I'll try and guess
what the code is--

795
01:01:34,566 --> 01:01:38,987
Copilot to navigator.
I'm ready with the fuel figures now.

796
01:01:39,112 --> 01:01:42,073
We have 109,000 total...

797
01:01:42,198 --> 01:01:44,951
...79,000 in the mains...

798
01:01:45,076 --> 01:01:47,829
...and 30,000 in the auxiliaries.

799
01:01:47,954 --> 01:01:49,831
And that works out
to roughly...

800
01:01:49,956 --> 01:01:53,376
...seven hours, 15 minutes
endurance from this time.

801
01:01:54,544 --> 01:01:59,174
DSO to captain. I have
an unidentified radar blip.

802
01:02:00,550 --> 01:02:03,178
Distance, 60 miles.

803
01:02:04,304 --> 01:02:07,474
Approximate speed, Mach 3.

804
01:02:07,599 --> 01:02:10,018
Looks like a missile tracking us.

805
01:02:12,437 --> 01:02:16,650
Confirmed, definite missile track.
Commence evasive action right.

806
01:02:22,864 --> 01:02:25,825
Missile still closing range.

807
01:02:26,618 --> 01:02:30,538
Distance, 50 miles.
Continue evasive action.

808
01:02:30,664 --> 01:02:32,832
Lock ECM to target intercept mode.

809
01:02:32,916 --> 01:02:37,045
ECM locked to
target intercept mode.

810
01:02:37,170 --> 01:02:39,547
Missile still tracking
and closing distance.

811
01:02:39,673 --> 01:02:43,718
Range, 40 miles.
Continue evasive action.

812
01:02:46,972 --> 01:02:50,850
Electronic Guidance Scrambler
to blue grid.

813
01:02:50,976 --> 01:02:54,396
Missile still tracking steady
and closing distance.

814
01:02:54,521 --> 01:02:56,481
Range, 30 miles.

815
01:02:58,692 --> 01:03:02,904
Missile still closing true and steady.
Continue evasive action.

816
01:03:10,495 --> 01:03:12,414
Range, 20 miles.

817
01:03:12,539 --> 01:03:16,376
Missile still closing distance
and tracking steady.

818
01:03:16,501 --> 01:03:18,878
Attack range gate
on maximum scan.

819
01:03:19,004 --> 01:03:21,381
Range gate on maximum scan.

820
01:03:21,506 --> 01:03:24,342
Range, 10 miles.

821
01:03:24,467 --> 01:03:28,388
Missile track deflecting.
Continue evasive action.

822
01:03:28,513 --> 01:03:31,725
Deflection increasing.
Range, eight miles.

823
01:03:31,850 --> 01:03:35,729
Deflection still increasing.
Range, six miles.

824
01:03:35,854 --> 01:03:38,481
Missile still deflecting.
Range, four miles.

825
01:03:44,321 --> 01:03:47,449
Range, two miles.
Missile still deflecting.

826
01:03:47,574 --> 01:03:49,909
Range, one mile.
Missile detonated!

827
01:03:56,541 --> 01:03:58,543
-Start lever to cutoff!
-Cutoff!

828
01:04:02,047 --> 01:04:03,506
Essential power!

829
01:04:11,890 --> 01:04:14,225
Re-select essential power!

830
01:04:14,350 --> 01:04:16,311
Essential power re-selected.

831
01:04:23,485 --> 01:04:24,861
The hatch is stuck!

832
01:04:28,448 --> 01:04:30,450
-Hit emergency power!
-Roger!

833
01:04:32,410 --> 01:04:35,205
-Extinguishers!
-Roger!

834
01:04:41,961 --> 01:04:45,173
-Transfer switches!
-Transferred!

835
01:04:45,298 --> 01:04:47,550
-Boost pumps off!
-Cut off!

836
01:04:59,312 --> 01:05:01,314
Fuel valves three, four and six!

837
01:05:13,827 --> 01:05:16,454
-Give me full power!
-Roger.

838
01:05:28,633 --> 01:05:32,345
"Peace on Earth. Peace on Earth."

839
01:05:35,348 --> 01:05:38,059
P-O-E.

840
01:05:38,184 --> 01:05:41,020
"Purity of Essence."

841
01:05:41,146 --> 01:05:44,691
O-P-O-E.

842
01:05:44,816 --> 01:05:45,900
O-P-E.

843
01:05:55,785 --> 01:05:57,370
Put your hands over your head.

844
01:05:57,495 --> 01:06:00,748
What the devil do you think
you're doing? Who are you?

845
01:06:00,874 --> 01:06:02,709
Put your hands over your head.

846
01:06:03,626 --> 01:06:06,379
What kind of suit
do you call that, fella?

847
01:06:06,504 --> 01:06:08,423
What do you mean, suit?

848
01:06:08,590 --> 01:06:10,925
This happens to be
an RAF uniform, sir.

849
01:06:11,092 --> 01:06:13,261
And I am Group Captain
Lionel Mandrake...

850
01:06:13,386 --> 01:06:15,388
...General Ripper's
executive officer.

851
01:06:15,513 --> 01:06:16,931
Where's General Ripper?

852
01:06:17,599 --> 01:06:19,893
He's dead, in the bathroom.

853
01:06:20,560 --> 01:06:23,688
-Where's the bathroom?
-Next to you.

854
01:06:32,989 --> 01:06:35,575
I don't know what stupid game
you're playing...

855
01:06:35,700 --> 01:06:38,119
...but I've got an idea
what the recall code is.

856
01:06:38,244 --> 01:06:40,580
I have to get in touch
with SAC headquarters.

857
01:06:40,705 --> 01:06:44,417
I said, put your hands over your head
and keep them there. Go on.

858
01:06:44,542 --> 01:06:46,127
-Got any witnesses?
-Withesses?

859
01:06:46,252 --> 01:06:48,171
What are you talking about?
He shot himself!

860
01:06:48,671 --> 01:06:50,256
While he was shaving, huh?

861
01:06:50,924 --> 01:06:56,054
Now, look, Colonel "Bat" Guano,
if that really is your name...

862
01:06:56,179 --> 01:06:59,974
...may I tell you that I have
a very, very good idea...

863
01:07:00,099 --> 01:07:03,102
...I think, I hope, I pray,
what the recall code is.

864
01:07:03,228 --> 01:07:04,979
It's some theme he kept repeating.

865
01:07:05,146 --> 01:07:09,150
A variation on "Peace on Earth"
or "Purity of Essence," one of those.

866
01:07:09,275 --> 01:07:13,112
Put your hands up on top of
your head. Start walking.

867
01:07:13,529 --> 01:07:16,407
Don't you know that General Ripper
went mad...

868
01:07:16,533 --> 01:07:19,827
...and sent the whole wing
to attack the Soviets?

869
01:07:19,953 --> 01:07:23,456
-What are you talking about?
-I'll tell you what I'm talking about.

870
01:07:23,581 --> 01:07:27,627
I'm gonna pick up this red telephone,
which is connected to SAC...

871
01:07:27,752 --> 01:07:29,671
...and I hope--

872
01:07:30,713 --> 01:07:32,840
Blast. Blast.

873
01:07:32,966 --> 01:07:37,720
Shot away, I expect, by one of your
men during this ridiculous fighting!

874
01:07:38,388 --> 01:07:40,348
Right.

875
01:07:40,473 --> 01:07:43,851
All right, Charlie, I've been
wasting too much time on you.

876
01:07:43,977 --> 01:07:47,730
I got a lot of wounded men outside.
Start walking.

877
01:08:10,003 --> 01:08:13,715
All the radio gear is out,
including the CRM 114.

878
01:08:13,840 --> 01:08:17,051
I think the auto-destruct mechanism
got hit and blew itself up.

879
01:08:21,639 --> 01:08:24,851
The fire is out.
The emergency power is on.

880
01:08:24,976 --> 01:08:28,396
Everything seems to
check out all right. Will advise.

881
01:08:28,521 --> 01:08:30,189
Roger. Navigator?

882
01:08:30,315 --> 01:08:35,528
I've worked out our rate of fuel loss
at approximately 162 per minute.

883
01:08:35,653 --> 01:08:38,573
This gives us a radius of action
sufficient to take out...

884
01:08:38,740 --> 01:08:42,035
...primary and secondary targets,
but we will not...

885
01:08:42,160 --> 01:08:46,873
...repeat, not be able to make it back
to any base or neutral country.

886
01:08:46,998 --> 01:08:52,587
However, we would have enough fuel
to ditch at weather ship Tango Delta...

887
01:08:52,712 --> 01:08:56,007
...grid coordinates 003 691.

888
01:09:00,762 --> 01:09:03,097
Well, boys,
we got three engines out...

889
01:09:03,264 --> 01:09:06,768
...we got more holes in us
than a horse trader's mule...

890
01:09:06,893 --> 01:09:09,187
...the radio is gone
and we're leaking fuel.

891
01:09:09,312 --> 01:09:12,607
If we was flying any lower,
we'd need sleigh bells on this thing.

892
01:09:12,774 --> 01:09:15,693
But we got one little budge
on them Russkies.

893
01:09:15,818 --> 01:09:17,779
At this height,
they might harpoon us...

894
01:09:17,904 --> 01:09:20,865
...but they sure ain't gonna spot us
on no radar screen.

895
01:09:32,043 --> 01:09:33,961
The other way.

896
01:09:34,087 --> 01:09:36,464
-Where are you taking me?
-To the main gate.

897
01:09:36,923 --> 01:09:38,299
Colonel!

898
01:09:38,424 --> 01:09:41,969
Colonel, I must know what you think
has been going on here.

899
01:09:42,095 --> 01:09:43,971
-You wanna know what I think?
-Yes.

900
01:09:44,097 --> 01:09:46,766
I think you're some kind
of deviated "prevert."

901
01:09:46,891 --> 01:09:49,560
I think Ripper found out
about your "preversion"...

902
01:09:49,685 --> 01:09:54,107
...and that you were organising some
kind of mutiny of preverts. Now, move!

903
01:09:54,524 --> 01:09:57,652
I don't know anything
about any planes attacking Russia.

904
01:09:57,819 --> 01:10:01,781
I was told get Ripper on the phone
with the president of the United States.

905
01:10:01,906 --> 01:10:06,494
Now, just one second.
You just said, "The president."

906
01:10:06,619 --> 01:10:08,788
What about the president?

907
01:10:08,913 --> 01:10:11,999
The president wants to speak
to General Ripper, doesn't he?

908
01:10:12,125 --> 01:10:14,627
Now, General Ripper is dead,
is he not?

909
01:10:14,752 --> 01:10:17,004
I am General Ripper's
executive officer...

910
01:10:17,130 --> 01:10:20,007
...S0 the president will want
to speak to me, won't he?

911
01:10:20,133 --> 01:10:23,845
There's a telephone box over there
and the line may be open.

912
01:10:23,970 --> 01:10:26,681
You wanna talk to
the president of the United States?

913
01:10:26,848 --> 01:10:29,642
I don't want to talk to him,
I've got to talk to him.

914
01:10:29,767 --> 01:10:33,354
And if you don't put that gun away
and stop this stupid nonsense...

915
01:10:33,479 --> 01:10:37,483
...the court of enquiry on this
will give you such a pranging...

916
01:10:37,608 --> 01:10:41,654
...you'll be lucky to end up wearing the
uniform of a bloody toilet attendant!

917
01:10:45,450 --> 01:10:47,326
Okay. Go ahead.

918
01:10:47,452 --> 01:10:50,913
Try and get the president
of the United States on the phone.

919
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:56,294
If you try any preversions in there,
I'll blow your head off.

920
01:11:09,474 --> 01:11:12,143
Operator? This is
Group Captain Lionel Mandrake.

921
01:11:12,268 --> 01:11:14,395
I'm speaking from
Burpelson Air Force Base.

922
01:11:14,520 --> 01:11:18,399
Something urgent has come up and I
want you to place an emergency call...

923
01:11:18,524 --> 01:11:21,569
...with President Merkin Muffley
in the Pentagon, Washington, D.C.

924
01:11:22,987 --> 01:11:26,199
Burpelson 39180.

925
01:11:27,366 --> 01:11:32,413
No, I'm perfectly serious.
The president of the United States.

926
01:11:32,538 --> 01:11:35,374
Oh, I'm sorry,
I haven't got enough change.

927
01:11:35,500 --> 01:11:38,878
Could you make this
a collect call, operator?

928
01:11:50,848 --> 01:11:53,267
Just one second, operator.

929
01:11:53,392 --> 01:11:56,229
They won't accept the call.
Have you got 55 cents?

930
01:11:56,354 --> 01:11:59,524
You don't think I'd go into combat with
loose change in my pocket, do you?

931
01:12:01,943 --> 01:12:04,779
Operator, look.

932
01:12:04,946 --> 01:12:08,407
Is it possible to make this
an ordinary trunk call?

933
01:12:08,533 --> 01:12:11,244
Well, what do you call it?
You know....

934
01:12:11,369 --> 01:12:14,372
Oh, station-to-station.

935
01:12:18,417 --> 01:12:21,963
Oh, blast!
I'm still 20 cents short.

